Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shijiazhuang, March 4 (XINHUA) -- The former royal 
summer resort of Chengde city in north China's Hebei Province 
will finally get rid of the many illegal buildings that affect 
its historical and natural beauties. 
  Local officials said all the 29 illegal modern buildings, 
totaling 81,000 sq m in the former summer retreat of emperors of 
the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) will soon be removed. 
  The 560-ha resort is under the protection of the national 
government. It attracts tens of thousands of tourists every 
year from both at home and abroad. 
  Already, the sources said, eight illegal buildings, 
including 
residential houses of city officials and an office building of 
the city bureau of cultural relics, have been removed. 
  According to the sources, all the removal work will be 
completed before this year's tourism season arrives. 

